Element categories!
==========================================================================
-<opening tag>content</closing tag>
-This whole thing is an element!

Nesting elements...
-<opening tag><inner opening tag>content</inner closing tag></closing tag>

Block
-appears on a new line
-content after will appear on a new line

Inline
-contained within blocks, tend to surround small parts

Empty/Void elements
-single tag elements often used to embed or insert something
<img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mdn/beginner-html-site/gh-pages/images/firefox-icon.png">


Attribues
============================================================================
<element_name attribute_name="...">

"anchor"
<a href=https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/HTML/Introduction_to_HTML/Getting_started title="Mozilla's Tutorial" target="_blank">
<p><a href=https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/HTML/Introduction_to_HTML/Getting_started title="Mozilla's Tutorial" target="_blank">Link</a></p>

Boolean attributes
<input type="text" disabled="disabled"> 
<input type="text" disabled>
<input type="text">

sometimes attributes written without values
they can only have one value--the attribute name

<a href=https://www.mozilla.org/>favorite website</a>
<a href=https://www.mozilla.org/ title=The Mozilla homepage>favorite website</a>
always include attribute quotes; otherwise some words will be thought of as booleans...

<!DOCTYPE html> - doctype
<html> - root element; wraps all content on the page
  <head> - container for stuff on the HTML that's not visible: keywords, page description, CSS, character set declarations, etc.
    <meta charset="utf-8"> - character set; just include this
    <title>My test page</title> - sets title in browser tab; title used when favoriting or bookmarking it
  </head>
  <body> - contains all content shown to users
    <p>This is my page</p>
  </body>
</html>

single quotes and double quotes are the same...
don't mix them together ("this is bad')
single quotes within double and vice-versa is okay ("It's okay!")
if you use a double quote within a set of doubles or a single within a set of singles--character entity references!

&code;

ex: &quot; - "

Whitespace is automatically trimmed down to one space; whitespace in code is often done for readability purposes

<!-- comment --> for both single line and multi-line comments
